§ 3. ALPHA STATUS DISCLOSURE

  3.1  Any distribution of the Software must include the Alpha Version Notice
       (Part I) verbatim and in a prominent, user-accessible location.

  3.2  All user-facing materials associated with a distribution of the
       unmodified Software must carry an unambiguous statement that the
       software is an alpha release.

  3.3  ALPHA NOTICE EXEMPTION FOR CERTIFIED DERIVATIVE WORKS: A Derivative
       Work distributed under a distinct name per § 6 is exempt from the
       requirement to carry the Alpha Version Notice if and only if ALL of
       the following conditions are met:

         (a) The Derivative Work has been independently tested and documented
             as suitable for its stated purpose by the distributing party;

         (b) The distributing party publishes a clear written certification
             statement identifying the specific version tested, the testing
             methodology employed, and the scope of warranted use;

         (c) The distributing party assumes full liability for the warranted
             use of the Derivative Work and does not pass liability back to
             the Neuro Project Contributors;

         (d) The Derivative Work is labeled as a "fork of Neuro" per § 5 and
             does not imply Neuro Project endorsement of the stability claim.

  3.4  You may not represent the unmodified Software to end users as
       production-ready or suitable for mission-critical use.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

§ 4. DOCUMENTATION OF MODIFICATIONS

  4.1  If you distribute a modified version of the Software, you must:

         (a) Mark each modified source file with a header comment identifying
             it as modified, the date of modification, and the modifying party;

         (b) Include a plaintext CHANGES file at the root of the distribution
             summarizing all material changes, authors responsible, and dates.
             Changes must be documented per release. Cumulative logs that
             knowingly omit intermediate material changes do not satisfy
             this requirement;

         (c) Not represent or imply that a modified version is the original,
             unmodified Neuro project.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

§ 5. MANDATORY ATTRIBUTION

  5.1  Any distribution of the Software, whether in source or binary form,
       must include the following attribution in a prominent, user-accessible
       location (such as a README, About page, splash screen, or NOTICE file):

         Based on Neuro (https://github.com/PanzerPeter/Neuro)
         Copyright (C) 2024–2026 Neuro Project Contributors

  5.2  All existing copyright notices in the Software must be preserved
       verbatim in all copies and Derivative Works.

  5.3  Attribution must not be placed in a manner that is effectively
       inaccessible to an ordinary end user — for example, exclusively within
       minified bundles without a corresponding readable NOTICE file, or
       buried within undocumented internal configuration structures.

  5.4  You may truthfully state that your Derivative Work is "based on Neuro"
       or "derived from the Neuro project", provided such statement is
       accompanied by the attribution in § 5.1 and the disclaimer in § 6.3.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

§ 6. NAMING AND IDENTITY OF DERIVATIVE WORKS

  6.1  Derivative Works must be distributed under a name that is clearly and
       meaningfully distinct from "Neuro" so as not to create confusion
       regarding the origin or official status of the project.

  6.2  You may not use any of the following, or names confusingly similar
       thereto, in the name of a Derivative Work without explicit prior written
       consent from the Neuro Project:

         — "Neuro" as a standalone product or project name;
         — "Neuro Engine", "NeuroAI", "NeuroPlatform", or any compound
           name in which "Neuro" is the dominant identifying element;
         — The official Neuro project logotype, icon set, or visual identity.

  6.3  You must include, in user-visible documentation, an explicit statement
       that your Derivative Work is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or an
       official release of the Neuro Project.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

§ 7. SOURCE AVAILABILITY FOR BINARY DISTRIBUTIONS

  7.1  If you distribute the Software or any Derivative Work in compiled,
       binary, or otherwise non-human-readable form, you must:

         (a) Include a plaintext NOTICE file at the root of the distribution
             containing the URL or written mechanism by which complete
             Corresponding Source may be obtained at no additional charge;

         (b) Ensure that source availability at the stated URL is maintained
             for no less than three (3) years from the date of the binary
             distribution.

  7.2  Corresponding Source must include all materials necessary to reproduce
       the distributed binary, including build scripts, dependency lists, and
       any toolchain configuration required for reproducible builds.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

§ 8. RESTRICTIONS ON COMPETITIVE AI REPRODUCTION

This section creates contractual obligations that Recipients accept upon
performing any copyright-regulated act with the Software. These obligations
are grounded in contract and trade secret law, not solely in copyright, and
are not intended to restrict independent development or lawful reverse
engineering for interoperability.

  8.1  PROHIBITION ON COMPETITIVE AI REPRODUCTION

       You agree not to engage in Competitive AI Reproduction (§ 1.5) of
       this Software. For clarity, this prohibition requires all three of
       the following elements to be present simultaneously before a violation
       exists:

         (a) An AI System is used to process the Software's source code or
             documentation as a primary input;

         (b) The output of that AI System constitutes a material portion of
             a new software product; and

         (c) That new software product directly competes with the Software in
             the same market category.

       The absence of any one of elements (a), (b), or (c) means no violation
       of this section has occurred.

  8.2  MULTI-STAGE PIPELINE EXTENSION

       The prohibition in § 8.1 extends to deliberate multi-stage workflows
       in which an AI System analyzes this Software specifically to produce
       an artifact (analysis, specification, blueprint) that is then used as
       a generation prompt for a competing codebase, where the intent and
       causal chain between analysis and competing output is documentable.

  8.3  RESTRICTION ON NON-PUBLIC PROPRIETARY ELEMENTS IN TRAINING DATA

       You agree not to use the Non-Public Proprietary Elements (§ 1.6)
       identified in PROPRIETARY.md as AI training data or fine-tuning data
       for the specific purpose of enabling an AI System to reproduce those
       elements in a competing product. General training on publicly available
       code that incidentally includes publicly posted versions of this
       Software is not prohibited by this section.

  8.4  PERMITTED AI-ASSISTED ACTIVITIES

       Notwithstanding §§ 8.1–8.3, the following are expressly permitted:

         (a) Using AI Systems to assist in writing contributions to this
             Software submitted back to the official project under this
             License;

         (b) Using AI Systems for personal code comprehension, debugging,
             or learning about the Software for the purpose of lawful use;

         (c) Using AI Systems to generate test cases, documentation
             improvements, or accessibility enhancements contributed back
             to the project;

         (d) Academic or research analysis of the Software, provided the
             resulting work does not constitute Competitive AI Reproduction;

         (e) Using AI Systems to build software that interoperates with, or
             builds upon, the Software in a non-competitive manner;

         (f) Any AI-assisted use of the Software that does not meet all three
             elements of § 8.1.

  8.5  RESPONSIBILITY FOR DIRECTED VIOLATIONS

       If an AI System acting under your explicit direction and on your behalf
       commits an act prohibited under §§ 8.1–8.3, and you had actual knowledge
       that such direction would result in a prohibited act, you are the
       responsible party for that violation. Automated acts by AI Systems
       operating without your specific direction or knowledge do not constitute
       a violation by you under this section.

  8.6  ACKNOWLEDGMENT OF LEGAL UNCERTAINTY

       The parties acknowledge that the legal landscape governing AI training
       and AI-assisted development is evolving. This section is drafted as a
       contractual obligation between the parties and is not intended to assert
       rights beyond what applicable law permits. If any provision of this
       section is found to be unenforceable under applicable law, the remaining
       provisions of this section shall be construed to achieve the nearest
       enforceable equivalent consistent with the intent expressed herein.

