===============================================================================
  PART VI — ENFORCEMENT
===============================================================================

§ 12. LICENSE TERMINATION

  12.1 Your rights under this License terminate automatically upon any
       material breach of its terms. Material breach includes:

         (a) Failure to include required attribution (§ 5);
         (b) Failure to disclose Alpha status when required (§ 3);
         (c) Failure to document modifications (§ 4);
         (d) Use of prohibited names or trademarks (§§ 6, 9);
         (e) Failure to provide source for binary distributions (§ 7);
         (f) Engaging in Competitive AI Reproduction in violation of § 8.1;
         (g) Using Non-Public Proprietary Elements as AI training data in
             violation of § 8.3;
         (h) Engaging in Commercial Distribution without authorization (§ 2.5).

  12.2 CURE PERIOD: Upon written notification of a material breach from the
       Neuro Project, you have thirty (30) calendar days from receipt of such
       notification to cure the breach. If you cure the breach within the
       cure period, your rights are automatically reinstated without
       further action required. Rights are permanently terminated only if:

         (a) You fail to cure a notified breach within thirty (30) days; or

         (b) You commit the same category of breach a second time after
             having previously cured a breach of that category.

  12.3 The thirty-day cure right in § 12.2 applies to all breaches except
       deliberate, willful Competitive AI Reproduction under § 8.1, which
       is not curable without written consent of the Neuro Project.

  12.4 Termination of your rights does not affect the rights of third parties
       who received valid copies from you prior to the termination event,
       provided those third parties remain in compliance with this License.

  12.5 Failure by the Neuro Project to promptly enforce any provision of this
       License does not constitute a waiver of that provision or of any right
       to enforce it in the future.

