§ 15. GOVERNING LAW AND DISPUTE RESOLUTION

  15.1 Governing Law. This License shall be construed and enforced in 
     accordance with the laws of Hungary, without regard to conflict-of-law 
     provisions. Any legal action or proceeding arising under this License 
     shall be brought exclusively in the courts located in Budapest, Hungary, 
     and the parties hereby consent to personal jurisdiction and venue therein.

  15.2 Dispute Resolution. Any dispute arising out of or relating to this 
     License that cannot be resolved informally within sixty (60) days of 
     written notice shall be resolved by binding arbitration in accordance 
     with the UNCITRAL Arbitration Rules in force at the time. The appointing 
     authority shall be the Arbitration Court attached to the Hungarian Chamber 
     of Commerce and Industry. The place of arbitration shall be Budapest, 
     Hungary, though proceedings may be conducted virtually by mutual agreement. 
     The language of the arbitration shall be English.

  15.3 Where mandatory local law renders arbitration unenforceable, disputes
       shall be resolved in the courts of the jurisdiction specified in § 15.1.

  15.4 Nothing in this License prevents either party from seeking emergency
       injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction to prevent
       irreparable harm pending arbitration.

§ 16. SEVERABILITY WITH FALLBACK HIERARCHY

  16.1 If any provision of this License is held unenforceable by a court of
       competent jurisdiction, that provision shall first be modified to the
       minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable, preserving original
       intent to the maximum extent possible.

  16.2 If modification is not possible, the unenforceable provision shall be
       severed, and all remaining provisions shall continue in full force.

  16.3 In the specific case that the Competitive AI Reproduction restriction
       (§ 8.1) is found unenforceable as a contract term, the parties agree
       it shall be re-construed as a trade secret misappropriation claim to
       the extent any Non-Public Proprietary Elements (§ 1.6) were involved,
       and as a breach of confidence claim to the extent permitted by
       applicable law.

